as Cranmer Hall in Sculthorpe (Norfolk), Cranmore in Shalfleet (Isle of Wight), Cranmer Bottom in Selborne and Cranmore in Aldershot (both Hampshire), and East and West Cranmore (Somerset), all named from Old English <i>cran</i> ‘crane’ + <i>mere</i> ‘lake, pool’ or <i>mōr</i> ‘moor, marshy ground’. See also   Cranmore  , with which there may have been some confusion."],"variants":[{"name":"Cranmore","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): variant of   Cranmer  ."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Cranmer was born about 1320, in Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. He married Matilda de Sutterton in 1354, in Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1398, in Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 79."},"et":{"Abt 1320–1398":"umbes 1320–1398","1336–1398":"1336–1398","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1320–1398":"1320–1398","1336":"1336","1356":"1356","Abt 1320":"umbes 1320","1354":"1354","1398":"1398","1320":"1320","Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sutterton, , Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Locherworth, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1320–1398":"noin 1320–1398","1336–1398":"1336–1398","1356–Male":"1356–Kuollut","1320–1398":"1320–1398","1336":"1336","1356":"1356","Abt 1320":"noin 1320","1354":"1354","1398":"1398","1320":"1320","Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sutterton, , Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England","Locherworth, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Midlothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1320–1398":"environ 1320–1398","1336–1398":"1336–1398","1356–Male":"1356–Décédé","1320–1398":"1320–1398","1336":"1336","1356":"1356","Abt 1320":"environ 1320","1354":"1354","1398":"1398","1320":"1320","Sutterton, Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Angleterre","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Sutterton, , Lincolnshire, England":"Sutterton, Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Angleterre","Locherworth, Edinburgh, Midlothian, Scotland":"Edinburgh, Midlothian, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Hugh Cranmer est né environ 1320, à Nottinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Matilda de Sutterton en 1354, à 